const INDUSTRIES = [
  {name:`Airline`,icon:`✈️`,content:`VALUE_CHAIN\nNetwork & Fleet Planning: Route network design, fleet acquisition or leasing, airport slot procurement, fuel sourcing and price-hedging strategies\nGround Operations: Passenger check-in and boarding, baggage and cargo handling, aircraft turnaround — cleaning, refueling and loading — and MRO scheduling\nIn-Flight Operations: Flight deck operations and navigation, cabin crew service delivery, regulatory compliance, onboard catering and ancillary amenities\nCommercial & Revenue Management: Dynamic yield management, multi-channel ticket distribution (website, app, OTAs, travel agents), loyalty programs, corporate tie-ups and alliance partnerships\nPost-Flight & Customer Experience: Feedback management, complaint resolution and compensation, customer retention and re-engagement§§MARKET_STRUCTURE\nIndia is the 3rd largest domestic aviation market globally by passenger volume, with domestic traffic crossing 150 million passengers annually\nDomestic market is effectively a duopoly — top 2 carriers (IndiGo and Air India) together hold ~85-90% market share; ~10-15 airlines operate in total\nInternational segment: India's share of global air traffic is ~4%; multiple full-service and low-cost international carriers compete\nScheduled Air Transport: Domestic (e.g. IndiGo, SpiceJet) and International (e.g. Air India, Emirates)\nNon-Scheduled / Charter: Air taxi and charter operators; Air Cargo: DHL, Blue Dart, Air India Cargo§§PORTERS\nBargaining power of suppliers|High|Oligopoly in aircraft manufacturing (Boeing, Airbus); engine duopoly (GE, Rolls-Royce); jet fuel supplied by PSU oil companies with limited pricing flexibility\nBargaining power of buyers|Moderate|Individual travellers have low switching costs and can easily compare fares; corporate/bulk buyers negotiate significant discounts\nThreat of new entrants|Low|High capital intensity, complex regulatory approvals (DGCA, bilateral ASAs), slot constraints at major airports, and brand trust create strong barriers\nThreat of substitutes|Moderate|Vande Bharat and premium trains are a real alternative for distances under 500 km; video-conferencing has reduced some business travel\nCompetitive rivalry|High|~15 carriers offering largely undifferentiated service compete aggressively on price; low switching costs amplify rivalry§§REVENUE\nTicket Revenue (core passenger fares across cabin classes)\nAncillary Passenger Revenue: Baggage fees, seat upgrade/selection, onboard retail, travel insurance\nCargo Revenue: Freight and mail transport\nLoyalty & Partnerships: Frequent flyer redemptions, co-branded credit cards, hotel and car-hire tie-ups§§COSTS\nAviation turbine fuel (ATF) — largest cost at ~40-50% of total operating expenses; USD-denominated, volatile\nMaintenance, Repair & Overhaul (MRO) — ~20-25% of costs; one of the largest recurring expenditure heads\nLabour costs and airport/navigation user charges — ~13-15%; aircraft lease rentals (USD-denominated, INR depreciation is a risk)§§KPIS\nASM (Available Seat Miles)|Seats x miles flown — measures capacity deployed\nRPM (Revenue Passenger Miles)|Passengers x miles flown — measures actual demand\nPassenger Load Factor|RPM / ASM — seat utilisation; IndiGo consistently achieves 85%+\nCASM (Cost per Available Seat Mile)|Operating cost / ASM — unit cost efficiency\nRASK (Revenue per Available Seat Mile)|Total revenue / ASM — unit revenue health§§PESTEL\nEnvironmental|India mandates 1% SAF (Sustainable Aviation Fuel) blending for domestic airlines; ICAO's CORSIA scheme applies to international routes\nLegal|Airline Operator Permit (AOP) required from DGCA; 100% FDI allowed under automatic route; bilateral Air Service Agreements govern international routes\nEconomic|Rising middle class expanding India's air-travel penetration (currently ~5% of population fly annually); jet fuel price volatility and USD/INR exchange rate are key financial risks§§TERMS\nMRO (Maintenance, Repair & Overhaul)|Activities to ensure airworthiness; can be done in-house or outsourced; a major cost head for all carriers\nDGCA|Directorate General of Civil Aviation — India's aviation regulator; issues AOPs, oversees safety and fare monitoring\nOTA (Online Travel Agency)|e.g. MakeMyTrip, Cleartrip — key distribution channel; typically commands 5-12% commission\nYield|Average revenue earned per passenger per kilometre — a pricing health metric`},
  {name:`Automobiles`,icon:`🚗`,content:`VALUE_CHAIN\nInbound Logistics: Sourcing of steel, aluminium, rubber, plastics and electronics; vendor development and management; inbound warehouse handling\nManufacturing: Primary production (casting, forming, stamping), secondary processing (machining, welding, painting), sub-assembly, main assembly line, quality control and testing\nOutbound Logistics: Finished goods warehousing, multi-modal distribution to dealer yards, channel incentive management\nMarketing & Sales: Brand advertising, pricing and promotional schemes, digital and dealer network marketing, test-drive and experience programmes\nAfter-Sales: Authorised service network, warranty fulfilment, extended AMC plans, spare parts supply, connected services (telematics, OTA updates)§§MARKET_STRUCTURE\nIndia is the 3rd largest automobile market in the world by volume, and the world's largest two-wheeler market\n2W: ~70-80% of volumes — Hero MotoCorp, Honda, TVS lead; EV scooters (Ola Electric, Ather) disrupting rapidly\nPV: ~15-25% — Maruti Suzuki leads (~40% share); SUV mix rising above 50% of PV sales; Tata, Hyundai, Mahindra are key challengers\nCV: ~4-7% — Tata Motors and Ashok Leyland dominate; M&HCV tied to infrastructure and mining cycles; LCV driven by last-mile logistics boom\n3W: ~1-3% — fast EV adoption, passenger and cargo applications; Bajaj and Piaggio lead§§PORTERS\nBargaining power of suppliers|Low|Large pool of Tier-1 and Tier-2 ancillary suppliers; OEMs increasingly sourcing globally, limiting any one supplier's leverage\nBargaining power of buyers|High|Price-sensitive consumers cross-shop brands extensively; transparent online price discovery (CarDekho, CarWale) and high dealer competition reduce OEM pricing power\nThreat of new entrants|Low|Massive capex requirement (greenfield plant ~Rs.3,000-5,000 Cr), long product development cycles (3-5 years), tight dealer-network moats; EVs are creating a new entry window\nThreat of substitutes|Moderate|Urban metro expansion and app-based ride-hailing (Ola, Uber) provide an alternative; work-from-home has reduced commuter demand in metro cities\nCompetitive rivalry|High|Established incumbents plus aggressive new EV players; rapid model refresh cycles (18-24 months) intensify competition§§REVENUE\nVehicle sales — core OEM revenue\nAfter-sales service and labour charges at authorised service centres\nExtended warranty, accessories and Annual Maintenance Contracts (AMC)\nVehicle financing and insurance facilitation — high-margin adjacent revenue§§COSTS\nRaw materials (steel, aluminium, rubber, semiconductors) — ~55-60% of vehicle cost\nLabour and manufacturing overheads\nDealer margins and retail channel incentives — typically 3-6% of ex-showroom price\nAdvertising, marketing and product launch costs§§KPIS\nUtilisation Rate|Actual production output / installed capacity — factory efficiency benchmark\nCycle Time|Total time to move a vehicle through the assembly line from start to finish\nEffective Labour Rate (ELR)|Revenue generated per billed labour hour at service centres — after-sales efficiency metric\nInventory Days|Average number of days of finished vehicle stock held at plant and dealer yards§§PESTEL\nTechnological|Government mandate of 20% ethanol blending in petrol by 2025-26; OEMs accelerating LFP/NMC battery EV platforms; CNG/hybrid adoption rising in fleet segment\nLegal|CAFE fuel-economy targets, mandatory 6 airbags for all cars from Oct 2023, OBD-II compliance, ELV recycling guidelines\nEnvironmental|BS-VI Phase 2 Real Driving Emissions from Apr 2023; life-cycle battery sustainability is an emerging regulatory focus§§TERMS\nOEM (Original Equipment Manufacturer)|The vehicle brand that assembles and sells cars (Maruti, Hyundai, Tata)\nADAS (Advanced Driver-Assistance Systems)|Safety features like AEB, lane-keep assist — increasingly mandatory in new cars\nWarranty Claims Rate|Number of warranty claims per 100 vehicles sold — quality and reliability indicator`},
  {name:`Cement`,icon:`🏗️`,content:`VALUE_CHAIN\nRaw Material Sourcing: Long-term leasing of limestone quarries (key competitive moat); supply contracts for coal, fly ash, gypsum and other additives\nInbound Logistics: Plant siting close to limestone source to minimise freight; rail, road and coastal shipping for other input materials\nManufacturing Process: Quarrying & crushing → pre-blending → raw mill → clinker kiln → cooler → finish grinding → blending → packing; high capital intensity with strong economies of scale\nDistribution: High freight-intensity; rail-road mix with coastal and bulk terminals; warehousing network; direct large-order supply to infrastructure projects and RMC plants\nSales & Marketing: Contractor and mason relationship management; dealer network for bagged retail; bulk pricing for institutional buyers; regional pricing driven by freight economics§§MARKET_STRUCTURE\nIndia is the world's 2nd largest cement producer (~8% of global capacity) with installed capacity of ~650-700 MTPA\nTop 5 players (UltraTech, Ambuja-ACC, Shree Cement, Dalmia) account for ~54% of capacity; strong regional oligopolies exist\nBy product: OPC 43/53 grade; blended (PPC, PSC, Composite); White cement and wall putty; Specialty grades (SRC, rapid-hardening, oil-well cement)\nBy end-use: Retail housing (bags) ~65%; Infrastructure/RMC/bulk ~25%; Industrial/commercial ~10%\nBy region: North and Central are price-competitive; South has structural overcapacity; East is fastest growing with under-served demand§§PORTERS\nBargaining power of suppliers|Medium|Government controls licensing of coal and limestone reserves; companies backward-integrate into captive power and coal mining to reduce dependence\nBargaining power of buyers|Low|Retail buyers (masons, households) are price-takers; large infrastructure buyers and RMC companies have some negotiating leverage\nThreat of new entrants|Moderate|High capex, multi-year regulatory clearances for mines, limestone access scarcity and freight economics create strong entry barriers\nThreat of substitutes|Low|No economically viable substitute for cement in construction at scale; alternative materials are complementary, not replacements\nCompetitive rivalry|Moderate|Oligopolistic market with homogeneous product; pricing follows capacity utilisation cycles; rivalry intensifies during demand downturns§§REVENUE\nBulk cement sales (>90% of revenue) — volume x realisation per tonne\nPremium product mix (PSC, Composite, white cement, wall putty) drives higher per-tonne realisation\nValue-added services — technical assistance to contractors, admixture sales§§COSTS\nPower and fuel (coal for kiln) — ~28-32% of manufacturing cost; largest variable cost\nFreight and distribution — ~22-26%; the single biggest profitability differentiator across regions\nRaw materials (limestone, fly ash, gypsum, slag) — ~18-22%§§KPIS\nEBITDA/Tonne|Primary profitability metric; industry benchmark ~Rs.900-1,200 per tonne\nClinker Factor|Tonnes of clinker per tonne of cement — lower is better with blended cements\nKiln Utilisation Rate|Actual clinker production / kiln rated capacity\nLead Distance|Average freight km from plant or railhead to customer — primary driver of logistics cost§§PESTEL\nPolitical|Government's infrastructure push (NIP, PM Gati Shakti, PMAY) is the biggest demand driver; each Rs.1 lakh Cr of infra capex consumes ~8-10 MT of cement\nEconomic|Cement demand is highly correlated with GDP and construction cycles; monsoon seasonality affects Q1 volumes\nEnvironmental|Green cement (GGBS, Portland Composite) offers lower carbon footprint; fly ash utilisation is mandated for thermal power plant waste reduction§§TERMS\nClinker|The intermediate product from the kiln; ground with gypsum to make OPC cement\nSpecific Heat Consumption|GJ per tonne of clinker — key kiln fuel efficiency metric\nRMC (Ready-Mix Concrete)|Pre-mixed concrete delivered by transit mixers; drives bulk cement demand from large construction projects\nLead Distance|Average transport km from plant to customer — primary driver of distribution cost and regional profitability differences`},
  {name:`Defence`,icon:`🛡️`,content:`VALUE_CHAIN\nR&D and Technology: Basic and applied research in materials, propulsion and electronic systems; technology absorption through licensing and JVs with foreign OEMs\nProduction: Facility and production line setup; supply chain management for precision components; indigenisation of sub-systems\nQuality Assurance: Meeting stringent MIL-SPEC certification standards; high-precision engineering and reliability testing\nSales and Contracting: RFP response and bidding; offset obligation compliance; price negotiations with MoD; participation in Aero India, DefExpo and global trade shows\nDelivery, Integration and MRO: System integration with existing platforms; field-level maintenance training; long-term MRO support contracts (typically 10-30 years)§§MARKET_STRUCTURE\nIndia is the world's largest arms importer — transitioning to domestic production under Atmanirbhar Bharat; defence budget FY25 ~Rs.6.21 lakh crore\nDomestic production dominated by Defence PSUs (DRDO, HAL, BEL, BDL) — ~77% by value; private sector (L&T, Tata, Mahindra Defence) holds ~23% and growing\nForeign OEMs (Boeing, Lockheed Martin, Dassault, Airbus Defence) participate through JVs, Transfer of Technology (ToT) and offset fulfilment\nWeapons and Armaments (missiles, artillery, ammunition) — highest share of Indian exports (~Rs.21,000 Cr in FY24)\nPlatforms (fighter jets, warships, submarines, tanks) — largest segment by procurement value; Electronics and Communication (radar, drones, EW systems) — fastest-growing§§PORTERS\nBargaining power of suppliers|High|Heavy reliance on foreign OEMs for high-tech sub-systems; Positive Indigenisation Lists (PIL) banning import of 400+ items are gradually reducing but not eliminating this dependence\nBargaining power of buyers|Very High|Government is the sole buyer in India; full procurement control through DAP (Defence Acquisition Procedure); offset obligations shift significant power to the MoD\nThreat of new entrants|Low|Multi-year qualification cycles, security clearances, massive upfront R&D and production investment; limited to a handful of large private players\nThreat of substitutes|Very Low|No functional substitute for dedicated defence equipment; dual-use technology (drones, cyber) may blur lines at the margins\nCompetitive rivalry|Moderate|DPSUs dominate on legacy contracts; but growing private sector participation and foreign JV requirements are intensifying intra-market competition§§REVENUE\nGovernment procurement contracts (MoD) — dominant revenue source\nDefence exports (India's exports crossed Rs.21,083 Cr in FY24; target Rs.50,000 Cr by FY29)\nAfter-sales support, spare parts and MRO contracts (long-duration, recurring)§§COSTS\nR&D and technology licensing — high upfront, amortised over long programme life\nPlant, machinery and precision tooling capital expenditure\nRaw materials (specialty alloys, composites, electronics) and manufacturing labour (highly skilled)§§KPIS\nOrder Book Value|Total value of signed contracts not yet executed — indicates revenue visibility\nDelivery Compliance Rate|% of orders delivered on time per specification — contractual penalty exposure metric\nIndigenous Content Ratio (IC%)|% of a platform's value sourced domestically — regulated by DAP category\nR&D Intensity|R&D spend as % of revenue — innovation pipeline indicator\nExport Order Value|Total value of defence export orders received — strategic competitiveness measure§§PESTEL\nPolitical|Atmanirbhar Bharat and Make in India push; Positive Indigenisation Lists banning import of 400+ items; FDI limit raised to 100% under automatic route\nEconomic|India's defence budget growing at ~8-10% CAGR; offset obligations (minimum 30% of contract value) create domestic economic multiplier\nTechnological|Shift to high-tech asymmetric warfare — drones, AI-enabled systems, cyber and EW; DRDO and iDEX are catalysing domestic innovation§§TERMS\nOffset Obligations|Foreign vendors required to invest a defined % (typically 30%) of contract value into India's defence or aerospace sector\nTransfer of Technology (ToT)|Licensing of manufacturing know-how from foreign OEM to an Indian designated production agency\nDPSUs (Defence Public Sector Undertakings)|State-owned companies — HAL, BEL, BDL, BEML, MDL — that manufacture defence platforms and systems`},
  {name:`E-commerce`,icon:`🛒`,content:`VALUE_CHAIN\nInbound Logistics & Platform Setup: Seller/supplier onboarding, procurement and quality checks, platform technology development and product cataloguing\nWarehousing and Operations: Fulfilment centre operations, inventory management, demand forecasting, platform management and listing optimisation\nOutbound Logistics: Order processing and picking, packaging, last-mile delivery through captive fleet or 3PL partners; cross-border exports\nMarketing and Customer Acquisition: Performance marketing (Google, Meta), influencer-led social commerce, loyalty programmes, affiliate marketing\nAfter-Sales Service: Returns and exchange processing, customer support, dispute resolution, refund management and feedback loops§§MARKET_STRUCTURE\nIndia's e-commerce market is ~US$60-70 billion GMV (FY24/25) and among the fastest-growing in the world; projected to reach US$300 billion by 2030\nOligopolistic structure: Flipkart ~32%, Amazon ~28%, Meesho ~9% in retail; Reliance JioMart, Tata Cliq and ONDC are expanding challengers\nHorizontal Retail: Fashion, electronics, books, FMCG — core of Flipkart, Amazon\nVertical/Niche: Beauty (Nykaa), food/grocery (Blinkit, Zepto), pharma (PharmEasy), furniture (Pepperfry)\nTier 2/3 cities now contribute ~65% of new online shoppers — the next growth frontier; ONDC unbundling the stack creating new marketplace dynamics§§PORTERS\nBargaining power of suppliers|Moderate|Branded sellers with strong pull have leverage; undifferentiated commodity sellers depend on platform visibility algorithms\nBargaining power of buyers|High|Extremely price-sensitive with zero switching cost; cashback and coupon culture further raises price expectations; ROPO behaviour common\nThreat of new entrants|Moderate|Low barriers in marketplace model but high barriers in logistics infrastructure; 100% FDI in marketplace allowed but inventory-led model restricted for foreign players\nThreat of substitutes|High|Physical retail, quick-commerce (10-minute delivery) and live-shopping formats are all competing for share of wallet\nCompetitive rivalry|High|Flipkart vs Amazon price wars; Meesho disrupting through ultra-low ASPs; JioMart leveraging Reliance Retail offline network; intense customer acquisition spending§§REVENUE\nCommission/Take Rate on GMV (typically 8-20% depending on category)\nSubscription and Prime/Plus membership fees\nAdvertising revenue (sponsored listings, banner ads) — fast-growing, high-margin\nLogistics and fulfilment revenue from sellers using platform warehousing\nFinancial services: co-branded credit cards, EMI facilitation, BNPL§§COSTS\nLast-mile delivery and returns logistics — ~15-20% of GMV; single largest cost\nCustomer acquisition cost (CAC) through discounts, coupons and ad spend\nWarehousing and fulfilment centre infrastructure and operations§§KPIS\nGMV (Gross Merchandise Value)|Total value of goods sold — primary scale metric\nTake Rate|Revenue / GMV — monetisation efficiency measure\nAOV (Average Order Value)|Total revenue / number of orders\nCAC (Customer Acquisition Cost)|Marketing and discount spend / new customers acquired\nSCAR (Shopping Cart Abandonment Rate)|1 minus cart-to-order conversion — reveals checkout friction§§PESTEL\nTechnology|GenAI-powered personalisation, AR/VR virtual try-on, voice commerce; quick-commerce enabled by dark store microfulfilment\nEnvironmental|Sustainable packaging mandates; EPR rules for plastic packaging; EV delivery fleet adoption\nLegal|100% FDI permitted in marketplace model but restricted in inventory-led model; ONDC promoting open-network architecture; Consumer Protection (E-Commerce) Rules 2020\nSocial|Tier 2/3 cities are the next growth engine; vernacular language and voice interfaces expanding non-metro user base§§TERMS\nROPO (Research Online, Purchase Offline)|Consumer behaviour of browsing online but buying in physical stores — a key conversion challenge\nBNPL (Buy Now Pay Later)|Short-term typically interest-free credit at checkout — Simpl, LazyPay, Amazon Pay Later\nD2C (Direct-to-Consumer)|Brands selling directly to end consumers without intermediaries — Mamaearth, boAt, Sugar Cosmetics as examples`},
  {name:`Education`,icon:`📚`,content:`VALUE_CHAIN\nInfrastructure and Curriculum Design: Setting learning outcomes, building physical and digital infrastructure, developing core curriculum content and pedagogical frameworks\nStudent Acquisition and Enrolment: Marketing and admissions campaigns, student counselling, application processing and scholarship programmes\nInstruction and Delivery: In-class and hybrid teaching, lab and practical training, extracurricular and co-curricular activity management\nAssessment and Outcomes Tracking: Examination design and conduct, continuous assessment, learning analytics, student progress monitoring and feedback loops\nPlacement, Alumni and Employer Relations: Career counselling, internship and placement facilitation, alumni network management, employer engagement and industry tie-ups§§MARKET_STRUCTURE\nIndia has the world's largest education system — 250M+ school students, 40M+ in higher education; sector valued at ~US$180 billion\nK-12: ~1.5 million schools; 70% govt/aided; CBSE and state boards co-exist; private school segment growing rapidly\nHigher Education: 1,000+ universities and 40,000+ colleges; elite IITs/IIMs vs mass private colleges; foreign university campuses now permitted under NEP 2020\nTest Prep and Coaching: ~Rs.60,000 Cr industry; Allen, FIITJEE, Unacademy, PhysicsWallah dominate; Kota model well established\nEdTech: Byju's, Unacademy, PhysicsWallah, Vedantu; market consolidated post-2021-22 funding winter; profitability now a priority over growth§§PORTERS\nBargaining power of suppliers|Moderate|Quality faculty and skilled educators are in short supply, especially in STEM and at higher education level; infrastructure suppliers are commoditised\nBargaining power of buyers|Moderate|Limited choice of quality higher education institutions gives them pricing power; K-12 and coaching segments are more competitive, giving buyers more options\nThreat of substitutes|Low to Moderate|Formal offline education still commands high trust in India; but EdTech is a growing substitute for coaching and supplementary learning\nThreat of new entrants|Moderate|Regulatory compliance (UGC, AICTE, state affiliations) creates barriers in formal education; EdTech has low entry barriers\nCompetitive rivalry|High|Intense competition among private players for limited high-quality students; high LTV per student incentivises aggressive acquisition spend§§REVENUE\nTuition and course fees — core revenue; often cross-subsidise weaker programmes\nAncillary fees: hostel, transport, food, lab, examination fees\nResearch grants and government funding (for deemed universities)\nCorporate tie-ups, sponsored certifications and value-added programmes§§COSTS\nPayroll (faculty and non-teaching staff) — typically 40-60% of operating expenses in higher education\nInfrastructure costs (building maintenance, utilities, technology, capex for labs and equipment)\nContent development, licensing and platform costs (critical for EdTech)§§KPIS\nPass/Success Rate|% of students passing board exams or clearing competitive tests — reputation driver\nStudent-to-Teacher Ratio|Regulatory benchmark; UGC mandates ~10:1 for engineering, ~15:1 for management\nPlacement Rate and Average Package|Primary marketing metric for engineering/management colleges\nStudent Retention Rate|% of enrolled students completing the full programme\nStudent Acquisition Cost|Cost to recruit and enrol one new student — critical for EdTech unit economics§§PESTEL\nPolitical|National Education Policy 2020 — multidisciplinary education, 5+3+3+4 school structure, permission for foreign universities, vocational integration from grade 6\nLegal|UGC, AICTE, NCTE are the main regulatory bodies; 100% FDI permitted under automatic route; equivalence norms for online degrees still evolving\nEconomic|India's rising disposable income and aspiring middle class drive premium education spending; student loan penetration increasing (currently ~12% of higher-ed students)§§TERMS\nUGC|University Grants Commission — apex regulatory body for universities and higher education in India\nAICTE|All India Council for Technical Education — regulates technical education: engineering, management, architecture\nNEP 2020|National Education Policy — India's most sweeping education reform enabling academic flexibility, multidisciplinary learning and foreign university entry\nLMS (Learning Management System)|Digital platform (Moodle, Canvas) for course content delivery, student tracking and assessments`},
  {name:`Hospitality`,icon:`🏨`,content:`VALUE_CHAIN\nSupply Chain and Procurement: Restaurant and bar supplies, furniture and fittings, linen, toiletries, kitchen raw materials, maintenance consumables\nWorkforce Management: Recruitment and training of front-of-house and back-of-house staff, admin and management development, attrition management\nOperations: Reservations and front desk, housekeeping, concierge and guest relations, F&B service, maintenance and facilities management\nSales and Marketing: Brand advertising, loyalty programme management, membership deals, seasonal promotional offers, corporate account management\nDistribution: Own website and app, global distribution systems (GDS), OTAs (MakeMyTrip, Booking.com, Expedia), travel agents and corporate travel desks§§MARKET_STRUCTURE\nIndia's hospitality market is ~Rs.2 lakh Cr (FY24); among the fastest-growing globally, driven by domestic tourism, MICE and international arrivals\nMarket is highly fragmented — large unorganised segment co-exists with branded chains; organised premium hotels hold ~30% of room inventory\nLuxury and Upper Upscale: IHCL (Taj), Marriott (India's fastest-growing chain), Hyatt, Oberoi, ITC Hotels\nMidscale and Economy: OYO (world's largest budget chain by room count), Lemon Tree, Treebo — digitally aggregated budget segment\nHomestays and Alternate Accommodation: Airbnb India growing rapidly; competes for leisure travellers in metro and leisure destinations§§PORTERS\nBargaining power of suppliers|Moderate|Property owners and landlords have leverage in prime locations; skilled hospitality staff are in short supply post-COVID; food and beverage suppliers are largely commoditised\nBargaining power of buyers|Moderate|Individual travellers are highly price-sensitive and quick to switch via OTAs; corporate accounts and MICE organisers command volume-based discounts; loyalty programme stickiness reduces premium churn\nThreat of new entrants|Low (luxury) / Moderate (budget)|High capex to build and brand a 5-star property (Rs.1-3 Cr per key in metro cities); asset-light aggregator model (OYO) has lowered entry barriers for budget segment\nThreat of substitutes|High|Airbnb and homestay platforms offer authentic, often cheaper alternatives; co-living spaces compete for long-stay travellers; video-conferencing reduces some MICE demand\nCompetitive rivalry|High|Dense supply in metro cities with thin margins; high fixed costs of vacant rooms create aggressive pricing; OTA transparency enables instant comparison§§REVENUE\nRoom tariffs (ADR x Occupancy) — primary revenue (~55-60% of total)\nFood and Beverage — restaurants, in-room dining, banquets (~25-30%)\nMICE and events (conferences, exhibitions, weddings) — growing high-margin segment\nAncillary services: spa, pool, laundry, business centre§§COSTS\nLabour and payroll — ~35-40% of revenue; highly labour-intensive industry\nFood, beverage and consumable materials\nEnergy costs (electricity, fuel for kitchens and HVAC) — ~6-8% of revenue\nRenovation, refurbishment and regular maintenance capex§§KPIS\nOccupancy Rate|Rooms occupied / total rooms available; industry benchmark 65-75% for 5-star hotels\nADR (Average Daily Rate)|Room revenue / rooms sold — pricing effectiveness\nRevPAR (Revenue per Available Room)|ADR x Occupancy = Total room revenue / total available rooms; composite performance metric\nGOP (Gross Operating Profit) per Room|Rooms revenue minus departmental operating costs per available room§§PESTEL\nTechnology|AI-based dynamic pricing, contactless check-in (NFC, digital keys), chatbot concierge; revenue management systems (RMS) adopted widely\nEnvironmental|Growing demand for Green Key and LEED certifications; sustainability features (solar power, water recycling) becoming a booking differentiator\nSocial|Rise of Bleisure (business + leisure travel); workcations; demand for unique experiential stays (heritage hotels, wellness retreats); solo female travel growing§§TERMS\nOTA (Online Travel Agency)|Platform aggregating hotel inventory — Booking.com, Expedia, MakeMyTrip; typically charges 15-25% commission\nMICE|Meetings, Incentives, Conferences and Exhibitions — the corporate events segment; high-margin and drives weekday occupancy\nRevPAR Index (RGI)|Hotel's RevPAR / competitive set's RevPAR — measures relative market performance\nADR (Average Daily Rate)|Average revenue earned per occupied room per night — the core room pricing metric`},
  {name:`Insurance`,icon:`🛡`,content:`VALUE_CHAIN\nProduct Design and Actuarial Pricing: Product development (life, health, motor, crop), actuarial risk modelling, premium rate setting and product regulatory approval\nDistribution and Sales: Agent and bancassurance channel management, DSA/broker network, digital direct sales, sales force productivity and incentive planning\nUnderwriting: Individual and group risk assessment, policy issuance, asset management of premium float, reinsurance arrangements\nClaims Management: First notice of loss (FNOL), claim investigation, fraud detection, claim settlement and disbursement, litigation management\nCustomer Service and Retention: Policy servicing, renewal management, grievance redressal, cross-sell and upsell, data-driven CRM§§MARKET_STRUCTURE\nIndia's insurance penetration is only ~4% of GDP (global average ~7%), indicating significant underpenetration and growth opportunity\nLife Insurance: LIC holds ~57% market share by new business premium; private players (SBI Life, HDFC Life, ICICI Pru, Max Life) collectively hold ~43% and growing\nNon-Life Insurance: New India Assurance leads with ~12.8% market share; motor, health and crop are the largest sub-segments\nHealth Insurance: Standalone health insurers (STAR Health, Niva Bupa, Care) growing at 20%+ CAGR; corporate group health is a large segment\nInsurtech: Acko, Digit, Onsurity disrupting distribution and claims with digital-first models§§PORTERS\nBargaining power of suppliers|Moderate|Limited number of qualified reinsurers (Munich Re, Swiss Re, GIC Re) have leverage; IT vendors for policy admin systems have moderate influence\nBargaining power of buyers|Moderate|Individual buyers have low power; large corporate clients and government (crop insurance tenders) have significant negotiating power\nThreat of new entrants|Moderate|IRDAI licensing is selective but not prohibitively difficult; bancassurance partnerships and digital distribution have lowered entry costs; BigTech (Jio, Amazon) entering the space\nThreat of substitutes|Low|No direct substitute for insurance risk transfer; however government welfare schemes (PMJAY) partially substitute private insurance\nCompetitive rivalry|High|~24 life and 30+ non-life insurers; price competition intense in motor and term life; differentiation through claims speed, digital UX and wellness programmes§§REVENUE\nGross Written Premium (GWP) — premiums received before reinsurance cession\nInvestment income from premium float (especially critical for life insurers; life float is 10-30 year duration)\nFee income from group administration, reinsurance facilitation§§COSTS\nClaims and loss ratios — largest expense; rising health claims inflation is a structural pressure\nOperating expenses — agent commissions (15-35% first year premium for life), bancassurance fees, digital platform costs\nReinsurance premiums (net of recoveries)§§KPIS\nPolicy Renewal Rate|% of policies renewed at maturity — retention and customer satisfaction proxy\nClaims Settlement Ratio|Claims settled / claims received; IRDAI publishes annual rankings; high ratio is a trust signal\nLoss Ratio|Claims incurred / net premiums earned; industry benchmark ~70-80% for non-life\nCombined Ratio|Loss Ratio + Expense Ratio; below 100% means underwriting profit\nPersistency (13th Month)|% of life policies still active after 13 months — indicator of product suitability and mis-selling§§PESTEL\nPolitical|PMJAY (Ayushman Bharat) government health scheme covers 500 million people; IRDAI's Bima Sugam is India's unified insurance marketplace\nEconomic|Rising financial awareness and nuclear family structures boosting term and health insurance; inflation driving up claim costs\nTechnological|AI/ML in underwriting, fraud detection and claims triage; telematics-based motor insurance (pay-as-you-drive); wearable integration in health policies§§TERMS\nSum Assured|Amount payable to the policyholder or nominee on the occurrence of the insured event\nPolicy Term|Duration for which the insurance policy remains active\nULIP (Unit Linked Insurance Plan)|Life insurance product with market-linked investment component — combines protection and wealth creation\nBancassurance|Distribution of insurance products through bank branches — SBI Life and Axis Max Life are leading examples`},
  {name:`IT & ITES`,icon:`💻`,content:`VALUE_CHAIN\nSolution Architecture and Product Design: Understanding client requirements, defining technology stack, solution blueprinting, selecting development platforms and tools\nDevelopment and Engineering: Agile/waterfall software development, data engineering, cloud migration, QA/testing, platform integration\nProduct and Service Delivery: SaaS deployment, managed services, application maintenance; customer onboarding and go-live support\nSales, Marketing and Account Management: Pre-sales solutioning, bid management, client retention and account growth, analyst relations\nSupport and Operations: L1/L2/L3 helpdesk, SLA management, performance monitoring, upgrades and patches, subscription billing management§§MARKET_STRUCTURE\nIndia's IT-BPM industry revenue is ~US$254 billion in FY24 (NASSCOM); direct employment of ~5.5 million professionals; contributes ~8% of India's GDP\nTop 3 — TCS, Infosys, HCL Tech — with a combined market cap exceeding US$250 billion dominate enterprise IT; Wipro, Tech Mahindra, L&T Tech form the second tier\nIT Services: Application development & maintenance, cloud services, infrastructure management — ~48% of industry revenue\nBPM (Business Process Management): Customer support, F&A, HR outsourcing, KPO — ~19-20% of revenue; Genpact, WNS, Mphasis are leaders\nER&D and Software Products: Industrial design, embedded software, SaaS — ~20%; fastest-growing, higher-margin segment; major verticals are BFSI (~30%), Retail/CPG (~15%), Healthcare (~12%)§§PORTERS\nBargaining power of suppliers|High|Cloud infrastructure monopolies (AWS, Azure, GCP) wield pricing power; niche talent pools (AI/ML engineers, cloud architects) command premium\nBargaining power of buyers|Moderate to High|Multi-vendor strategies and large RFPs give enterprise clients leverage; but switching costs (integration complexity, institutional knowledge) create stickiness\nThreat of new entrants|Moderate|Capital-light model enables new niche players; GenAI start-ups disrupting at the margin; but scale, certifications (ISO, SOC2, CMMI) and client trust are moats\nThreat of substitutes|High|GenAI tools (GitHub Copilot, ChatGPT Enterprise) automating coding and documentation; low-code/no-code platforms reducing custom development demand\nCompetitive rivalry|High|Intense competition among large Indian IT firms on talent, pricing and GenAI capability; global players (Accenture, Capgemini, IBM) are direct competitors for large deals§§REVENUE\nTime and Material (T&M) and Fixed Price engagement fees\nManaged services and outcome-based contracts (growing model)\nSaaS subscription and platform licences\nIP licensing, royalties from proprietary platforms§§COSTS\nEmployee costs — ~55-65% of revenue; attrition and wage inflation are key variables\nTechnology stack — cloud infrastructure, software licences, data centre costs\nSelling and G&A expenses — bid costs, visa and travel costs for onshore delivery§§KPIS\nEmployee Utilisation Rate|Billable hours / total available hours — the most watched operational metric\nAttrition Rate|Annual % of employees leaving; industry benchmark ~15-20% p.a.\nRevenue per Employee|Total revenue / headcount — productivity and pricing power indicator\nCSAT (Customer Satisfaction Score)|Measures client satisfaction with service delivery\nMTTR (Mean Time to Recovery)|Average time to restore a failed system — operational quality metric§§PESTEL\nTechnological|GenAI adoption is the defining macro theme — 75% of enterprises integrating AI by 2025; cloud-first and platform-led delivery replacing traditional project models\nPolitical|US H-1B visa policy uncertainty is a key risk for onshore delivery model; India-UK and India-EU FTAs likely to ease services trade\nEconomic|India's IT is export-dominated (~75% of revenue from US and Europe); Union Budget earmarked Rs.2,000 Cr for India AI Mission in FY25§§TERMS\nSaaS (Software as a Service)|Cloud-delivered, subscription-licensed software — Salesforce, ServiceNow, Freshworks are examples\nGenAI (Generative AI)|AI models (GPT-4, Gemini) that generate text, code, images — transforming software development and BPM workflows\nHyperscalers|AWS, Azure and GCP — cloud platform providers whose capabilities underpin most modern IT delivery\nFreemium|Offering core product free, charging for premium features — growth model for SaaS start-ups`},
  {name:`Logistics`,icon:`🚚`,content:`VALUE_CHAIN\nDemand Forecasting and Network Design: Customer segmentation, demand modelling, hub-and-spoke network design, SLA and pricing structure definition\nCapacity and Carrier Management: Fleet procurement or leasing (road, rail, air, ocean), carrier partnerships, route bidding, freight contract management\nFirst Mile and Collection: Order pickup from origin, scanning and labelling, packaging, customs clearance for cross-border, last-mile dispatch instructions\nSorting and Line-Haul: Multi-modal long-haul transit to regional distribution hubs, automated sorting by destination and shipment type\nLast Mile and Returns: Doorstep delivery with ePOD, failed delivery management, returns and reverse logistics processing, customer billing and dispute resolution§§MARKET_STRUCTURE\nIndia's logistics industry is ~US$250 billion (FY24); logistics costs as a % of GDP (~14%) are high vs developed markets (~8%) — a key inefficiency being addressed\nHighly fragmented — ~12 million trucks operated by individual owners; top 10 players hold less than 10% share; consolidation accelerating\nExpress and B2C Logistics: Delhivery, Blue Dart, DTDC, Ecom Express — serving e-commerce; Delhivery is India's largest by parcel volume\nFreight and FTL: Blackbuck, Porter, Rivigo — tech-enabled freight platforms; rail freight (Indian Railways) handling bulk commodities\nWarehousing and 3PL: Mahindra Logistics, DHL, Allcargo — integrated supply chain services; cold-chain logistics growing with pharma and food sectors§§PORTERS\nBargaining Power of Suppliers|Moderate|Truck manufacturers and fuel companies have influence on variable costs; automation and EV adoption may shift supplier dynamics over time\nBargaining Power of Buyers|High|Large e-commerce players and FMCG companies have enormous bargaining power; multi-vendor approach limits any single 3PL's pricing leverage\nThreat of New Entrants|Moderate|Asset-light digital freight brokers have low entry costs; asset-heavy 3PL and cold-chain require significant capex\nThreat of Substitutes|Low|Physical movement of goods has no true substitute; digital commerce acceleration increases, not reduces, logistics demand\nCompetitive Rivalry|High|Intense price competition on standard freight; differentiation on speed (same-day), reliability (OTIF%) and technology (real-time tracking) gaining importance§§REVENUE\nFreight charges by mode (road, rail, air, ocean) and shipment type (FTL, LTL, parcel)\nValue-added services — packaging, labelling, kitting, temperature-controlled storage\nTechnology platform and SaaS fees (TMS, WMS)\nSupply chain consulting and managed services§§COSTS\nTransportation costs (diesel/fuel, vehicle lease, tolls, permits) — ~45-55% of revenue for road logistics; highly sensitive to crude oil prices\nPersonnel costs (drivers, delivery executives, hub staff) — ~20-25%\nWarehouse and hub rentals; technology platform development and maintenance§§KPIS\nOTIF (On-Time In-Full %)|% of orders delivered correctly and on time — the primary SLA metric\nCost per Shipment / Cost per kg|Unit cost efficiency benchmark across networks\nCapacity Utilisation|% of truck or container capacity filled — asset productivity metric\nDamage and Claims Ratio|% of shipments with damage or service complaints — quality metric\nFirst Attempt Delivery Rate|% of deliveries successfully completed on the first attempt — last-mile efficiency§§PESTEL\nPolitical|PM Gati Shakti National Master Plan (Rs.100 lakh Cr infra investment); dedicated freight corridors (EDFC, WDFC) reducing rail transit time by ~40%\nEconomic|E-commerce and quick-commerce growth is the biggest demand driver; GST implementation simplified inter-state logistics by removing checkpost delays\nSocial|Consumer expectation of same-day and next-day delivery is becoming a baseline standard\nTechnological|IoT-enabled real-time tracking, automated sorting at fulfilment centres, EV last-mile fleets, AI-driven route optimisation\nEnvironmental|FAME II subsidy for EV commercial vehicles; green warehousing (LED, solar, rainwater harvesting) gaining traction§§TERMS\nFTL / LTL|Full Truck Load / Less Than Truck Load — two primary freight modes; FTL for dedicated full loads, LTL for consolidated part-loads\n3PL (Third-Party Logistics)|Outsourced logistics provider managing warehousing, transport and fulfilment\nePOD (Electronic Proof of Delivery)|Digital delivery confirmation via app, replacing paper-based PODs\nEDFC / WDFC|Eastern and Western Dedicated Freight Corridors — high-speed freight rail lines reducing logistics cost from 14% to ~8% of GDP`},
  {name:`Oil & Gas`,icon:`⛽`,content:`VALUE_CHAIN\nExploration: Securing government petroleum licences, seismic surveys and geological mapping of on/off-shore blocks, exploratory drilling\nProduction: Reservoir development planning, drilling and well completion, extraction of crude oil and natural gas, enhanced oil recovery\nTransport and Storage: Crude transport via pipelines, tankers and coastal shipping; crude storage in tank farms; gas transport via pipelines and LNG terminals\nDownstream Refining: Atmospheric and vacuum distillation, cracking, reforming and hydrotreating to convert crude into petrol, diesel, ATF, LPG, naphtha and petrochemicals\nMarketing and Distribution: Wholesale and retail distribution of refined products via petrol stations (IOCL, BPCL, HPCL networks), piped gas distribution, LPG cylinder supply chains§§MARKET_STRUCTURE\nIndia is the world's 3rd largest oil consumer (5.2 million barrels/day in FY24) and the 2nd largest refiner in Asia with 24 refineries (total capacity ~254 MMTPA)\nUpstream dominated by ONGC and Oil India (public sector); Cairn India is the largest private upstream player\nDownstream dominated by the OMC trio — IOCL (~44% refining market share), BPCL (~16%), HPCL (~12%); Reliance operates the world's largest single-location refinery (Jamnagar)\nNatural Gas: GAIL is the dominant gas transporter and marketer; CGD (city gas distribution) is a fast-growing segment — IGL, MGL, Adani Gas\nIndia imports ~85% of its crude oil — highest import dependence among major economies; Gulf and Russia are key sources§§PORTERS\nBargaining power of suppliers|High|OPEC+ controls global crude prices; oilfield services companies (Schlumberger, Halliburton) wield power in upstream; LNG terminals are limited in number\nBargaining power of buyers|Moderate|Industrial consumers buy in bulk and negotiate; retail petrol/diesel is government-regulated pricing, limiting buyer leverage\nThreat of new entrants|Low|Exploration blocks require government allocation; refinery greenfield capex is Rs.50,000-80,000 Cr; pipeline infrastructure requires regulatory approvals and right-of-way\nThreat of substitutes|Moderate|EVs, renewable energy and green hydrogen are long-term structural substitutes; pace of transition is accelerating but fossil fuel demand remains robust to 2035+\nIndustry rivalry|High|OMC competition on retail fuel, petrochemicals and LPG; private sector (Reliance) competes aggressively on refining and retail fuel§§REVENUE\nCrude oil, condensate and NGL production sales — upstream\nRefined product sales (petrol, diesel, ATF, LPG, naphtha) — downstream\nPipeline tariff and transportation fees\nPetrochemical product sales; LNG re-gasification and CGD distribution margins§§COSTS\nExploration, drilling and well development capex — ~50-60% of upstream capex\nCrude oil procurement cost — largest variable cost for refiners\nRefinery energy consumption (fuel and power), catalyst and chemical costs; transportation and storage logistics§§KPIS\nBPD (Barrels Per Day)|Standard crude production rate measurement; ONGC produces ~420,000 BPD\nGRM (Gross Refining Margin)|Difference between crude cost and realised value of output per barrel\nRefinery Utilisation Rate|Actual throughput / nameplate capacity; Indian refineries average ~105-110% utilisation\nReserve Replacement Ratio (RRR)|New reserves added / production — sustainability of upstream reserves§§PESTEL\nPolitical|India's ethanol blending programme (20% by 2025-26) reducing petrol import; strategic petroleum reserves (Padur, Visakhapatnam) for energy security; PNGRB regulates natural gas infrastructure\nEconomic|Global crude price volatility directly impacts India's CAD and inflation; India's forex outgo on energy imports ~US$100 billion annually\nEnvironmental|India's commitment to net-zero by 2070; transition to green hydrogen and offshore wind; carbon capture regulations expected in refining sector§§TERMS\nUpstream|Exploration and production (E&P) — where reserves are found and crude is extracted\nDownstream|Refining, marketing and distribution of refined petroleum products\nGRM (Gross Refining Margin)|Profitability measure for refiners — revenue from products minus crude cost\nCGD (City Gas Distribution)|Piped natural gas and CNG network serving households and vehicles in cities`},
  {name:`OTT`,icon:`📺`,content:`VALUE_CHAIN\nContent Acquisition and Original Production: Sports and film rights acquisition, co-production deals with studios, commissioning of regional language originals, live content production\nTechnology and Operations: Content localisation (subtitling, dubbing), DRM, CDN for low-latency streaming, app development across platforms (TV, mobile, web)\nDistribution: Native apps, smart-TV integrations, telco/operator billing and bundling partnerships, connected TV (CTV) and AVOD sticks (Fire TV, Chromecast)\nMarketing and Growth: Performance marketing, tentpole launch campaigns, sports-spike monetisation, content creator collaborations, SEO/app store optimisation\nSubscriber Management and Retention: Churn prediction and intervention, personalisation algorithms, parental controls, payment failure recovery, grievance redressal§§MARKET_STRUCTURE\nIndia is the world's largest OTT market by users (~550 million streaming video users in 2024) but among the lowest in ARPU (~US$1.5/month vs US$15+ in the US)\nYouTube holds ~92% of online video viewing time in India (AVOD); JioCinema's free IPL in 2023 permanently changed market dynamics\nSVOD (Subscription VOD): Netflix, Amazon Prime Video, Disney+ Hotstar — top 3 players hold ~67% of paid subscribers; Rs.149-299/month price points\nAVOD (Ad-supported VOD): MX Player, SonyLIV free tier, JioCinema — ad-funded model with mass reach\nHybrid/Bundled: Telco bundles (Jio, Airtel Xstream) reduce effective price and drive subscriber growth§§PORTERS\nBargaining power of suppliers|Moderate to High|Premium sports rights (IPL, BCCI) command billion-dollar bids; A-list studios/content creators have pricing power; but for general content, supply is abundant\nBargaining power of buyers|High|Zero switching cost between platforms; AVOD makes content consumption nearly free; price-sensitive Indian consumers churn at any price increase\nThreat of new entrants|Low|Scale requires hundreds of millions in content investment, sports rights and tech infrastructure; entry requires near-unlimited capital\nThreat of substitutes|Moderate|Short-video (YouTube Shorts, Instagram Reels) competes for entertainment time; gaming, podcasts and social media are indirect substitutes\nCompetitive rivalry|High|Content spending arms race; sports rights inflation; price cuts and free sports streaming intensifying competition§§REVENUE\nSubscription fees (SVOD) — recurring; premium tier at Rs.499-649/month\nAdvertising revenue (AVOD, in-stream ads) — high-volume, CPM-based; sports inventory commands premium\nContent licensing to other platforms and international distributors\nBrand integrations and sponsorships within original content§§COSTS\nContent rights acquisition and production — ~60-75% of revenue; the dominant cost; original content amortised over content life\nTechnology platform, CDN infrastructure, encoding and delivery\nCustomer acquisition (performance marketing) and subscriber re-acquisition after churn§§KPIS\nMAU (Monthly Active Users)|Total unique users in a month — reach and engagement metric\nARPU (Average Revenue Per User)|Revenue / subscribers — monetisation efficiency; India's ARPU is a fraction of global benchmarks\nChurn Rate|% of paid subscribers cancelling in a period; industry benchmark <5%/month for SVOD\nAverage Watch Time per User|Minutes or hours of content consumed per user per day — engagement depth\nFree-to-Paid Conversion Rate|% of free/trial users converting to paid plans — key AVOD monetisation metric§§PESTEL\nSocial|India's linguistic diversity (22+ official languages) drives demand for regional originals; Tamil, Telugu, Malayalam OTT content has gone pan-India\nTechnological|5G rollout and cheap mobile data (Jio ~Rs.10/GB) underpin streaming growth; smart TV penetration growing at 30%+ CAGR; AI-driven content recommendation increasing session depth\nLegal|DPDP Act imposes consent requirements; MIB content codes (IT Rules 2021) require a 3-tier grievance mechanism for OTT platforms§§TERMS\nSVOD / AVOD / TVOD|Subscription / Ad-supported / Transaction (pay-per-view) Video on Demand — the three primary OTT monetisation models\nDRM (Digital Rights Management)|Content protection technology preventing piracy and unauthorised redistribution\nPeak Concurrency|Maximum simultaneous viewers during a live event; determines CDN capacity planning\nWindowing|Sequential release of content across formats — cinema then OTT then linear TV; OTT is now often Day 1 for major releases`},
  {name:`Payments`,icon:`💳`,content:`VALUE_CHAIN\nConsumer/Payer: Initiates payment via mobile app (PhonePe, GPay), QR code, NFC, net banking or card; relies on convenience, speed and cost (MDR 0% for UPI)\nIssuing Bank/Wallet: Authenticates the payer, authorises or declines the transaction, manages card/account limits, shares interchange fee with network\nPayment Network: Routes and settles transactions between issuing and acquiring banks — NPCI (UPI, RuPay), Visa, Mastercard; earns network fees\nAcquiring Bank/PSP: Onboards merchants, provides POS terminals/QR codes, settles merchant funds (T+1 for UPI), manages chargeback disputes\nMerchant: Accepts payment, pays MDR (0% on UPI, ~1.5-2% on credit cards), reconciles settlements, manages refunds§§MARKET_STRUCTURE\nIndia's digital payments volume reached ~220 billion transactions in FY24, growing 35% YoY — among the highest growth rates globally\nUPI dominates: ~186 billion transactions (up 41.7% YoY), Rs.261 trillion in value; represents 83.7% of digital payment volume; PhonePe (~47%), Google Pay (~38%), Paytm (~10%) lead\nCards: Credit card usage growing (34% YoY) driven by rewards and EMI; debit card usage declining (29.5% YoY) as UPI substitutes\nB2B Payments: NACH (mandates), RTGS, NEFT — large-value, institutional; Razorpay, Cashfree, Juspay serve fintech/startup merchants\nIndia is exporting UPI globally — live in Singapore, UAE, France, UK; NPCI International is the vehicle§§PORTERS\nBargaining power of suppliers|Moderate|NPCI controls UPI rails and charges no MDR (zero-MDR policy); card networks (Visa, Mastercard) retain leverage on card interchange; cloud infrastructure is a supplier\nBargaining power of buyers|High|Zero MDR on UPI has made switching costless for consumers; merchants on UPI pay nothing; differentiation is now on UX, rewards and credit offerings\nThreat of new entrants|Low|NPCI licensing, RBI regulatory compliance, network effects of established players (PhonePe/GPay duopoly) and brand trust create high barriers\nThreat of substitutes|Moderate|Cash is still ~40% of consumer transactions by value; CBDC (Digital Rupee) is a potential long-term complement to commercial bank money\nCompetitive rivalry|High|UPI is commoditised; players compete on UX, credit products, merchant acquiring and financial services cross-sell; interchange compression squeezing revenue§§REVENUE\nMDR on card transactions (credit: ~1.5-2%; debit: ~0.5-0.9%; UPI: zero) — under regulatory pressure\nSubscription fees (SaaS pricing for payment gateway APIs — Razorpay, Cashfree)\nCross-sell revenue: insurance, investments, credit — high-margin, growing rapidly\nFloat income on wallet balances and settlement timing§§COSTS\nRegulatory compliance and licensing (PPI licence, PA licence, data localisation)\nTechnology infrastructure — real-time processing at billions of transactions requires massive redundant tech stack\nCustomer acquisition and merchant onboarding costs§§KPIS\nTPV (Total Payment Volume)|Total value of transactions processed — scale metric\nPayment Success Rate|% of transactions completing successfully (no technical failures or declines)\nChargeback Ratio|% of transactions disputed by customers — fraud and risk quality indicator\nTake Rate|Revenue / TPV — very low for UPI (~0.05%), higher for credit card processing (~1%)\nSystem Uptime|% of time payment system is operational; NPCI targets 99.9%+ for UPI§§PESTEL\nPolitical|RBI's zero-MDR policy for UPI constrains monetisation; cross-border UPI expansion creates new revenue pools; Digital India infrastructure (Aadhaar, UPI, DigiLocker) as public goods\nTechnological|India Stack (Aadhaar + UPI + eKYC + Account Aggregator) is the world's most advanced digital public infrastructure; ONDC extending open-network logic to commerce\nLegal|DPDP Act imposes data consent requirements; Payment Aggregator (PA) licensing by RBI; Consumer protection laws govern dispute resolution timelines\nSocial|Consumers now expect 24x7 instant, free payment mechanism — raising the bar for uptime and product experience§§TERMS\nMDR (Merchant Discount Rate)|Fee charged to merchants per transaction; 0% for UPI by govt mandate; ~1.5-2% for credit cards\nNPCI (National Payments Corporation of India)|Not-for-profit entity operating UPI, RuPay, FASTag, NACH, Bharat BillPay — India's core payments infrastructure\nUPI (Unified Payments Interface)|Real-time, interoperable payment system enabling bank-to-bank transfer via mobile; handles 83%+ of India's digital payment volume\nCBDC (Central Bank Digital Currency)|Digital Rupee (e-Rs.) — RBI-issued digital currency; retail and wholesale pilots underway`},
  {name:`Pharmaceuticals`,icon:`💊`,content:`VALUE_CHAIN\nResearch and Discovery: Target identification, drug candidate screening, pre-clinical testing; formulation science and licensing of pre-existing compounds; lifecycle extension for off-patent molecules\nDevelopment and Regulatory Approvals: Phase I/II/III clinical trials; applications to CDSCO (India), US FDA, EMA for marketing authorisation; patent filing and IP protection; tech transfer from R&D to manufacturing\nManufacturing: GMP-certified plant setup; API and excipient procurement; primary and secondary manufacturing; in-process quality control; serialisation and packaging\nSupply Chain and Outbound Logistics: Cold-chain distribution for biologics and vaccines; wholesale and distributor management; stockist and chemist retail network; export logistics to US, EU and emerging markets\nSales and Marketing: Medical representative (MR) detailing to doctors; trade marketing to chemists; DTC advertising for OTC products only; digital HCP engagement; brand management§§MARKET_STRUCTURE\nIndia's pharmaceutical industry is ~US$65 billion (FY24) — 3rd largest globally by volume and 14th by value; >70% is export-driven (primarily to US generics market)\nIndia supplies ~20% of global generic medicines by volume and ~60% of global vaccines; dominant position in US generics (Cipla, Sun Pharma, Dr. Reddy's, Lupin)\nBranded Generics (Domestic Market): Highly competitive, brand-driven; Sun Pharma, Abbott, Cipla, Mankind lead\nBiologics and Biosimilars: Fastest-growing segment; Biocon, Serum Institute, Bharat Biotech leading India's biosimilar exports\nCRAMS (Contract Research and Manufacturing Services): Divi's Laboratories, Aurobindo — supplying APIs and intermediates globally§§PORTERS\nBargaining power of suppliers|Low|API and excipient raw materials largely available from multiple domestic and Chinese suppliers; capital equipment from global vendors\nBargaining power of buyers|Medium|Retail consumers are price-takers; hospital chains, government tender agencies and state governments are large buyers with significant negotiating leverage; US generics subject to price pressure\nThreat of substitutes|Low|Substitutes for prescription drugs are limited; however, biosimilars substitute innovator biologics\nThreat of new entrants|Low|GMP plant investment is Rs.200-500 Cr+; US FDA/CDSCO inspections are complex; patent challenges require legal expertise; high regulatory barriers\nCompetitive rivalry|High|US generics market is hyper-competitive; NPPA controls prices on 370+ essential medicines; Indian generic companies also compete intensely for domestic brand share§§REVENUE\nDrug sales — branded generics (domestic), generics exports (US, Europe), API exports\nLicensing fees and milestone payments from innovator pharma partnering\nContract Manufacturing (CRAMS) revenue — steady margin, repeat business\nContract R&D services — CRO and CMO models§§COSTS\nR&D expenditure — ~5-8% of revenue for Indian generics; ANDA/NDA filing costs for US FDA approvals\nManufacturing (GMP compliance, energy, API procurement) — ~30-35%\nField force (medical reps) and trade marketing — ~15-20% of domestic revenue§§KPIS\nTime to Market|Period from drug discovery to first commercial sale — critical in generic launches (first-to-file 180-day exclusivity in US)\nRORC (Return on Research Capital)|Gross profits / prior-year R&D spend — R&D productivity\nGross Margin|60-75% for branded generics; lower for commodity generics and API\nANDA Filings Pending Approval|Abbreviated New Drug Applications awaiting US FDA approval — pipeline depth indicator for generic exporters§§PESTEL\nSocial|India's ageing population and rising prevalence of lifestyle diseases (diabetes, hypertension, obesity) are structural demand drivers for chronic disease medications\nLegal|PLI scheme for pharmaceuticals and APIs worth Rs.15,000 Cr promotes domestic API manufacturing; revised Schedule M (GMP) upgrades raise quality compliance standards; NPPA controls pricing of 370+ essential drugs\nPolitical|US FDA warning letters can immediately freeze exports from a facility; iDEX and PLI incentivising domestic formulation and API production§§TERMS\nAPI (Active Pharmaceutical Ingredient)|The biologically active component of a drug formulation; India is a major global API supplier\nANDA (Abbreviated New Drug Application)|US FDA approval pathway for generic drugs — does not require new clinical trials\nBiosimilar|A near-identical version of a biologic drug (protein-based) after patent expiry — a high-growth segment for Indian pharma\nGMP (Good Manufacturing Practice)|Regulatory framework ensuring pharmaceutical manufacturing quality and safety; mandatory for all export markets`},
  {name:`Power`,icon:`⚡`,content:`VALUE_CHAIN\nFuel and Resource Supply: Coal procurement (domestic via CIL and imports), natural gas supply, uranium for nuclear, solar module and wind turbine component supply chains\nPower Generation: Thermal power plants (coal/gas), large hydro, pumped storage, solar (utility-scale), wind farms, nuclear reactors; captive and cogeneration plants\nTransmission: High-voltage transmission lines (HVDC and HVAC) managed by PGCIL (central) and STUs (state); substation management; inter-regional grid integration\nDistribution and Retail: Low-voltage distribution by DISCOMs; smart meter rollout; last-mile reliability; billing and collection; RDSS upgrades\nTrading and Markets: Power Exchange India (PXIL, IEX) for spot and day-ahead trading; long-term PPAs with generators; open access for large industrial consumers§§MARKET_STRUCTURE\nIndia's total installed capacity crossed ~490 GW (as of July 2025); non-fossil fuel sources crossed 50% of installed capacity for the first time in 2025\nMarket share by ownership: Private sector ~55%, State sector ~23%, Central sector ~22%\nGeneration mix: Solar ~100 GW, Wind ~47 GW, Large Hydro ~47 GW, Nuclear ~7.5 GW; Coal remains the largest at ~220 GW but its share is declining\nTransmission: PGCIL manages ~180,000+ km of inter-state transmission lines; ATC (Aggregate Technical and Commercial) losses have fallen to ~17% from 30%+ a decade ago\nDistribution: 28 state DISCOMs distribute to end consumers; many loss-making; RDSS providing Rs.3.03 lakh Cr for upgrades§§PORTERS\nBargaining power of suppliers|Moderate|Coal India dominates domestic coal supply; solar module supply is China-dependent (BCD aims to change this); multiple equipment suppliers for renewables limit individual leverage\nBargaining power of buyers|Low|Industrial and commercial consumers are price-regulated; DISCOMs negotiate long-term PPAs; agricultural consumers receive subsidised/free power\nThreat of new entrants|Low (thermal) / Moderate (RE)|New thermal plant clearances are limited; auctions enable new RE developers; solar capex has fallen 80% over a decade, lowering barriers\nThreat of substitutes|Moderate|Rooftop solar plus battery storage is a partial substitute; industrial captive plants bypass DISCOM distribution\nCompetitive rivalry|High|RE sector has intense auction-based competition (L1 bidding); thermal IPPs compete for coal allocation and PPA tenders from state DISCOMs§§REVENUE\nTariff income (capacity charges + energy charges as per PPA) — primary for generators\nMerchant power sales on IEX (India Energy Exchange) — spot market, price-variable\nTransmission wheeling charges (for PGCIL and STUs)\nAncillary services revenue (frequency regulation, spinning reserves)§§COSTS\nFuel cost (coal, gas) — largest variable cost for thermal; ~40-50% of generation cost; government fuel supply agreements (FSA) mitigate risk\nInfrastructure capex (plant and equipment, transmission lines, substations) — long-duration, debt-financed\nOperations, maintenance and regulatory compliance§§KPIS\nPLF (Plant Load Factor)|Actual energy generated / maximum possible energy — thermal plant utilisation; coal PLF has declined to ~55-60% due to RE competition\nAvailability Factor|% of time the plant is available and ready to generate — reliability metric\nAT&C Losses|Aggregate Technical and Commercial losses including billing/collection inefficiency; national average ~17%\nDSCR (Debt Service Coverage Ratio)|Power project's ability to service debt from operational cash flows — project finance metric§§PESTEL\nPolitical|India's 500 GW non-fossil target by 2030; RDSS smart metering rollout; PM-KUSUM for solar in agriculture; DDUGJY and IPDS for rural electrification\nTechnological|Smart grid investments (AMI, SCADA, EMS) improving grid management; battery energy storage systems (BESS) enabling RE integration; green hydrogen emerging as storage option\nEnvironmental|India's pledge to reduce GDP emission intensity by 45% by 2030 vs 2005; COP26/28 commitments on coal phase-down; clean generation share hit fresh highs in 2025§§TERMS\nDISCOM|Distribution Company — responsible for last-mile power distribution to consumers; most are state-owned\nIPP (Independent Power Producer)|Private company generating and selling electricity; Adani Power, Torrent Power, JSW Energy are key IPPs\nPPA (Power Purchase Agreement)|Long-term contract (25 years) between generator and DISCOM for supply at agreed tariff — backbone of project finance for power plants\nPLF (Plant Load Factor)|Capacity utilisation metric for thermal plants — declining as renewables dispatch first`},
  {name:`Retail`,icon:`🏪`,content:`VALUE_CHAIN\nBuying and Merchandising: Vendor identification and negotiation, product range planning (line planning), demand and price forecasting, quality testing and vendor compliance\nSupply Chain and Inbound Logistics: Network optimisation, multi-modal transportation, cold-chain management for perishables, receiving and unloading, DC (Distribution Centre) operations\nStore Operations and Merchandising: Space planning (planogram), shelf replenishment, inventory allocation, in-store experience management, shrinkage control\nSales, Marketing and CRM: Promotions and discounts, loyalty programme management, digital marketing, cross-sell and upsell, in-store events\nAfter-Sales and Returns: Customer service, easy returns and exchange policy, reverse logistics (RVP, RTO), warranty and repair facilitation§§MARKET_STRUCTURE\nIndia's retail market is the 4th largest in the world at ~US$1.06 trillion (2024); projected to reach US$1.9 trillion by 2030; unorganised retail still ~85% but organised share rising\nE-retail GMV is ~US$60 billion (FY24/25); India has 200+ million online shoppers — 3rd largest online shopper base globally\nGrocery: BigBazaar (Reliance), Reliance Smart, DMart (value retail, consistently profitable), JioMart — largest segment by value\nFashion: Westside, Myntra, Zara, H&M; D2C brands (Nykaa Fashion, Snitch) gaining share\nQuick Commerce: Blinkit, Zepto, Swiggy Instamart — 10-minute delivery; disrupting daily needs and impulse purchases§§PORTERS\nBargaining power of suppliers|Moderate|Organised retailers with scale (Reliance, DMart) have strong supplier leverage; private label penetration gives additional control; FMCG majors retain some power due to brand pull\nBargaining power of buyers|High|Price transparency (Google Shopping, price comparison apps) eliminates information asymmetry; loyalty programmes create some stickiness but easy to exit\nThreat of new entrants|Moderate|Online retail entry is low-cost; offline retail requires real estate, supply chain and working capital investment — moats that protect incumbents\nThreat of substitutes|High|Offline vs online, quick-commerce vs weekly grocery, D2C vs branded retail — constant format disruption\nCompetitive rivalry|High|Intense multi-format competition; grocery operates at thin 2-4% net margins; Amazon and Flipkart continue to pressure traditional retail§§REVENUE\nCore merchandise sales — private label (own brand) generates 30-50% gross margin vs 20-30% for national brands\nLoyalty programmes and rewards redemption income\nAdvertising and promotional income from brands (vendor funding)\nValue-added services: extended warranty, home delivery charges, alterations§§COSTS\nCOGS and supply chain — largest cost; buying price, inbound freight, DC handling\nRetail lease — typically 5-12% of revenue in organised retail; prime location premium is significant\nShrinkage — theft, wastage and expiry (~1-2% of revenue; critical in fresh food)\nLabour and utilities for in-store operations§§KPIS\nSales per Square Foot|Net sales / total retail area — space productivity; DMart achieves Rs.30,000+/sqft, among the best globally\nGross Margin %|(Revenue minus COGS) / Revenue; grocery ~18-22%, fashion ~45-55%\nInventory Turnover|Net sales / average inventory — merchandise efficiency; DMart's ~12x is exceptionally high\nCustomer Retention Rate|Repeat buyers as % of total buyers — loyalty metric\nBasket Size / AOV (Average Order Value)|Revenue / transactions — cross-sell effectiveness§§PESTEL\nPolitical & Legal|100% FDI in single-brand retail; retail and wholesale traders classified as MSMEs for credit access; ONDC disrupting aggregator dominance\nEnvironmental|Single-use plastic ban driving packaging innovation; ESG disclosures by listed retailers; sustainability increasingly a consumer purchase factor\nSocial|Premiumisation trend co-exists with value retail growth in Tier 2/3; omnichannel shopping behaviour now mainstream§§TERMS\nPlanogram|Visual merchandising schematic defining product placement on shelves — maximises sales per facing\nPoS (Point of Sale)|System processing customer transactions; modern PoS integrates inventory, loyalty and payments\nShrinkage|Inventory loss from theft, administrative errors and damage — a key profitability leak in physical retail\nONDC (Open Network for Digital Commerce)|India's open commerce protocol unbundling the platform — buyer app, seller app and logistics separated, enabling SME participation`},
  {name:`Semiconductor`,icon:`🔬`,content:`VALUE_CHAIN\nRaw Materials and Equipment Supply: Silicon wafers (Shin-Etsu, Sumco — Japan-dominated), photomasks, specialty chemicals, inert gases; capital equipment — photolithography (ASML monopoly), etch, deposition, testing\nDesign (EDA and IP): Electronic Design Automation tools (Synopsys, Cadence), IP licensing (ARM — dominant in mobile), logic and chip design; India has 120+ global chip design centres (Qualcomm, Nvidia, Intel, NXP)\nFabrication (Foundry): Photolithography-based wafer processing at advanced nodes (3nm-28nm); TSMC (Taiwan) and Samsung dominate; GlobalFoundries, UMC for legacy nodes; India currently has no operational leading-edge fab\nOSAT (Outsourced Semiconductor Assembly and Test): Wafer dicing, die attach, wire bonding, encapsulation, final testing; Micron (Sanand), CG Power-Renesas, Kaynes Technology establishing in India\nEnd Market Distribution: To device manufacturers (Apple, Samsung), automotive OEMs (via Tier-1s like Bosch, Continental), distributor network; end markets — smartphones, laptops, EVs, IoT, defence§§MARKET_STRUCTURE\nGlobal market: ~US$580 billion (2024); projected to reach US$1 trillion by 2030; highly cyclical (boom-bust every 3-5 years)\nIndia imports ~95% of its semiconductor requirement (~US$27 billion/year) — almost entirely from Taiwan, South Korea and China — creating strategic supply chain vulnerability\nIndia's strength is in Design: 120+ design centres, ~400,000 VLSI design engineers (world's largest talent pool outside the US); Qualcomm, Nvidia, AMD, Intel, Broadcom all have significant India design presence\nChip segments: Logic chips (CPUs, GPUs, modems) — ~45% of market; Memory (DRAM, NAND flash) — ~30%; Wafer fab services — ~15%; IP licensing — ~5%\nIndia's emerging manufacturing: Tata Electronics (fab + OSAT), Micron Technology (OSAT in Gujarat), CG Power + Renesas, Kaynes + Kaynes Semicon — beneficiaries of India Semiconductor Mission§§PORTERS\nBargaining power of suppliers|High|ASML has a global monopoly on EUV lithography machines (>€100 million each); specialty chemicals from limited producers; silicon wafer duopoly (Shin-Etsu/Sumco)\nBargaining power of buyers|Moderate|Large customers (Apple, Samsung) have leverage; but high switching costs (node qualifications take 12-18 months) limit short-term buyer power\nThreat of new entrants|Very Low|A new leading-edge fab costs US$15-20 billion; requires 2-4 years to build and qualify; TSMC's yield advantage took decades to build\nThreat of substitutes|Very Low|No functional substitute for silicon-based integrated circuits; silicon photonics and compound semiconductors (GaN, SiC) emerging for specific applications, not replacements\nCompetitive rivalry|High|Intel vs AMD vs ARM (design); TSMC vs Samsung (foundry); memory is a cyclical commodity war (Samsung vs SK Hynix vs Micron)§§REVENUE\nChip sales — wafer-level pricing; logic chips are the highest-margin segment\nIP licensing royalties (ARM earns royalties on every ARM-based chip)\nOSAT services (assembly and test) — lower margin (~20-30% gross margin)\nFoundry services (wafer fabrication) — capital-intensive but high barrier moat§§COSTS\nCapital Expenditure (35-40%): Fab equipment depreciation dominates; TSMC spends US$30-35 billion/year in capex\nR&D (15-20%): Node advancement, process IP development; Intel, TSMC and Samsung each spend US$5-10+ billion/year\nRaw Materials and Consumables (20-25%): Silicon wafers, photomasks, process chemicals§§KPIS\nFab Utilisation Rate (%)|Production capacity in use; a 1% change can swing revenue by hundreds of millions given fixed cost structure\nYield (%)|Functional dies per wafer — quality and process maturity metric; TSMC's 3nm yield advantage is a core competitive moat\nRevenue per Wafer Start|Revenue generated per wafer processed — mix and pricing health indicator§§PESTEL\nPolitical|India Semiconductor Mission (ISM) — Rs.76,000 Cr incentive package; 50% capex subsidy for fabs, 30% for OSAT; US CHIPS Act, EU Chips Act and India ISM signal global supply chain diversification away from Taiwan\nSocial|India's 400,000+ VLSI engineers are a strategic national resource; fab process engineers (wet chemistry, metrology) are scarce globally — a key bottleneck for India's manufacturing ambitions§§TERMS\nFab (Fabrication Plant)|Factory where semiconductor wafers are processed; leading-edge fabs operate at 3-5nm nodes\nFoundry|A contract chip manufacturer (TSMC, GlobalFoundries) making chips designed by fabless companies (Qualcomm, Apple, AMD)\nOSAT (Outsourced Semiconductor Assembly and Test)|Post-fab packaging and testing; lower capital intensity than fab; viable India entry point\nEUV (Extreme Ultraviolet Lithography)|ASML-monopolised technology enabling sub-7nm chip manufacturing; critical and export-controlled`},
  {name:`Telecom`,icon:`📡`,content:`VALUE_CHAIN\nTower and Passive Infrastructure: Build, own and operate telecom towers under infrastructure sharing agreements; tower companies (Indus Towers, ATC India) provide passive sharing to multiple operators — reduces CAPEX by 60-70% vs each operator owning towers\nActive Equipment Suppliers: Radio access network (RAN) equipment, routers, switches, optical fibre — Nokia, Ericsson (post-Huawei ban); India pushing domestic manufacturing (ITI, HFCL)\nNetwork Integration: Turnkey integration of 4G/5G network software and hardware; network slicing, edge computing and OSS/BSS deployment\nNetwork Operator (MNO): Acquires spectrum at auction; owns and operates RAN, core network and transmission; delivers voice, data and broadband services; Jio, Airtel, Vodafone Idea are India's three private MNOs\nService Delivery: Consumer B2C services (prepaid/postpaid/broadband), enterprise B2B (cloud, IoT, SD-WAN, UC), wholesale (spectrum leasing, roaming agreements, submarine cable)§§MARKET_STRUCTURE\nIndia is the world's 2nd largest telecom market — 1,200 million subscribers, 85% tele-density; ~850 million data users (2024)\nPost-consolidation oligopoly: Jio (~40%), Airtel (~34%), Vodafone Idea (~19%) in wireless; BSNL/MTNL hold ~8.5% (PSU)\nWireless (mobile): ~900 million subscribers; India has one of the world's cheapest mobile data rates (~Rs.10/GB, a Jio-driven structural change)\nEnterprise B2B: Unified communications, IoT platforms, cloud services, SD-WAN — high-margin, growing segment for Airtel Business and Jio Business\n5G: India crossed 100 million 5G connections in record time (2023); 5G standalone (SA) networks being deployed for enterprise use cases (smart manufacturing, healthcare)§§PORTERS\nBargaining Power of Suppliers|Moderate|High switching costs once an operator standardises on Nokia or Ericsson; but India's dual-vendor policy limits monopolistic leverage; spectrum is auctioned by government at high prices\nBargaining Power of Buyers|High|India's price-sensitive consumers switch operators easily via MNP (600+ million port requests processed); ARPU at ~Rs.180-200/month is one of the lowest globally\nThreat of New Entrants|Low|Spectrum auction fees are astronomical (Jio paid Rs.88,000 Cr in 2022); tower infrastructure, core network and brand building create near-impenetrable barriers\nThreat of Substitutes|Moderate|OTT voice/video (WhatsApp, Zoom) substitute traditional calling; Starlink satellite broadband is an emerging alternative for rural coverage\nCompetitive Rivalry|High|Jio structurally reset industry economics through price disruption since 2016; Airtel repositioning as premium; Vi in financial stress; rational tariff hikes in 2024 signal consolidation§§REVENUE\nMobile data and voice plans (prepaid/postpaid/bundled) — Jio's Rs.155-599 range; Airtel's Rs.179-719 range\nBroadband (JioFiber, Airtel Xstream) — growing rapidly from low base\nEnterprise services (IoT, cloud, SD-WAN, UCaaS) — high-margin, sticky\nSpectrum leasing, national and international roaming, interconnect fees§§COSTS\nSpectrum costs — upfront auction price (CapEx) plus annual licence fees (~8% of AGR)\nNetwork infrastructure — RAN, core network, fibre backhaul, data centres\nCustomer acquisition — SIM distribution, retailer commissions, advertising for prepaid churn management§§KPIS\nARPU (Average Revenue Per User)|Monthly revenue / subscribers — Airtel ARPU (Rs.200+) is significantly higher than Vi (Rs.145), reflecting premium mix\nChurn Rate|Monthly % of subscribers porting out or disconnecting; reducing churn by 1% can add hundreds of crores in annual revenue\nNetwork Uptime|% of time network is operational; target 99.9%+; Airtel and Jio have best-in-class quality\nData Consumption per User|India average ~25 GB/month/user — one of the highest in the world\nSubscriber Market Share|% of total active subscribers — primary competitive metric; reported monthly by TRAI§§PESTEL\nTechnology|5G deployment enabling Industry 4.0 use cases (smart factories, remote surgery, precision agriculture); satellite broadband (OneWeb, Starlink) creating last-mile coverage; AI-driven network operations reducing OpEx\nLegal|TRAI regulates tariffs and quality of service; spectrum allocation via DoT; data localisation under DPDP Act; Huawei phase-out for network security\nEconomic|High interest rates increase burden of debt taken for spectrum auctions; tariff hikes in 2024 were the first since 2021 — signal of rational pricing restoring EBITDA margins; Vi's financial stress is a sector-wide risk\nPolitical|Ban and phase-out of Huawei equipment for privacy and national security; government revival of BSNL with Rs.89,000 Cr package§§TERMS\nARPU (Average Revenue Per User)|Core telecom profitability metric — India's ARPU is rising but still among the lowest globally\nMNP (Mobile Number Portability)|Allows subscribers to keep their number when switching operators — facilitates competition and consumer choice\nBTS (Base Transceiver Station)|The radio equipment at tower sites that communicates with mobile handsets\nMSISDN|The full mobile phone number (including country code) that uniquely identifies a subscriber on the network`}
];